Then he went back to London and dropped me and it took to 24 to get over him because I was depressed and gay. At 25 I met a man in the same political party, also 7 years older. We slept together & still friends.

We held hands and it was my first sober kiss. He said “you’re so young.” I was starting to trust someone romantically for the first time in my life. I had started to tell him some of the abuse of my childhood. He kissed me goodbye, near the uni library.

Anyway he decided to fuck me up emotionally after deciding not to sleep with me. He took me to the Lagan Towpath (I had never been) & told he he always came here with his ex gf. He told me he was thinking of moving back to NI. We walked and talked for a few hours.

He’s always been an incredibly respected activist of the left. Has like 12K followers on here now. I was 19 and poor and getting hell from family & community for challenging unionism. A working class girl infatuated with a middle class man who was giving me attention.

On NYE he appeared with 2 of his pals. So we didn’t have sex/he must have had a bit of a realisation of how young, vulnerable & naive I was. But I went into a deep depression at his rejection. And continuing to try to get his attention. Because he was 25! Worked for a MP!

Went to a family planning clinic to get the pill. I think this was abortion being illegal in NI & actually being gay. But it took me a hour to actually go inside. I had panic attacks in the loos. I didn’t want to have sex with him, fundamentally  - I wasn’t ready.

He said he would like to come along and that only he might need a place to stay after. I mean given his family home is in Belfast. He was wanting to sleep with me. I was terrified because I was a virgin but so flattered. Sent a flirty text.

Maybe as I’m autistic. But yeah months of texting and pursing me and a phonecall at one point. To he came home at Christmas and texted if there was any NYE house parties happening in Belfast. I mentioned one.

That was on my very first visit to London. We were in the same political party and I had just been appointed the volunteer youth wing chair. He saw me posting in a group on FB, and added me. It took me months to release he was sexually/romantically interested in me…

Seeing photos of young Russian children detained by police in Moscow for protesting the war and leaving flowers at the Ukrainian embassy. And the video of a 12 year old Palestinian girl being held down & beaten by Israeli soldiers. 

This is getting to me.
It took me 4 years to stop feeling angry and upset that Santa wasn’t real and emotionally accept it, another example.
It took 5 years to fully integrate being diagnosed as dyslexic and dyspraxic. That’s something I rarely think about now when it too used to cycle like this in my mind.

I read in my work training pack that autistic people will often repeat information as a way to process it…and that explains how my brain goes over and over and over traumas from different angles. And how I seem to cycle on tweeting about these things too.

I came to feel it was very cruel of me with my two degrees and the opportunity to develop self awareness and that I escaped all sorts of pressures and environments which make it harder to heal. With my life without daily killings. And they changed.

I forgive my parents because how can I expect working class parents, who grew up in dysfunctional homes and were abused by their parents, who grew up in poverty, who lived through the NI conflict. To be well adjusted?

And within all these generations there was love and warmth mixed with abuse and violence. My mum was so organised. Our home was tidy and our uniform perfectly ironed and 3 nutritional meals a day. We had the farm and animals. A lot of freedom in nature. Toys at Christmas etc.

With my mum’s parents. Some of their children see either my granny or my grandfather as the severe one. It’s probably a survival mechanism. A child needs to believe at least one parent is warm and kind. But that too, an abusive & dysfunctional family.

Not officially but if you give your child away to another adult to raise them. That’s adoption without the legal/State aspects. My Granny spoke of being depressed having child after child. 13 births from 1930 to 1950. Living in acute poverty.

My parents are not bad people. My dad’s mum was so abusive and controlling that she tried to guilt him into not marrying my mum and didn’t go to their wedding. My granny? Given up at birth, to her aunt. The only child not raised by her parents. She hated her siblings. Adoption.

I’m at a point where I’m glad I had no contact with social services or mental health services as a child. I & my brothers have very strong bonds. We’ve all overcome impacts of childhood & probably being together, sharing in the dysfunction. Helped us then and to heal.

I have weird feelings on the domestic abuse bill passing into law in NI. It will help people no doubt. My mum’s abuse of me easily went far past the limits of the law. And I fear we’ll see policing, prison, punishment used more than social services, support & rehabilitation.

Maybe being abused by my parents has made me overly serious and a deep thinker about the autonomy of a child but I think this is broadly, good. Especially as I hope to be a short-term foster carer in my 40s.

I am frequently pretty shocked at the detail by which many parents go into on social media about their children’s health and challenges and struggles. Most parents act like they own their children but you don’t. Children can’t truly consent to sharing of such information.

I have recently learnt that my oldest niece probably shares in one of my conditions but I won’t share on social media because it’s her information/life. Plus it’s not confirmed and she may not have it.
